    "case_number": "DP-2007-B6585, DP-2007-B6591, DP-2007-B6594, DP-2007-B6598",
    "citation": null,
    "decision_date": null,
    "industry": "Real Estate / Property Brokerage",
    "overview": "Four property agents complained that their personal data (NRIC number, date of birth, home address) were improperly disclosed by SLP Scotia to SLP International Property Consultants and then to the Council of Estate Agencies without consent during a corporate merger. The investigation examined whether the organisations breached the Consent Obligation under section 13 of the PDPA.",
    "pdpa_sections": [
      "s.13"
    ],
    "obligations": [
      "Consent Obligation"
    ],
    "individuals_affected": "4",
    "root_cause": "The organisations disclosed personal data of the complainants to effect a change in salesperson registration from SLPS to SLPIPC following an announced merger between the two related corporations.",
    "outcome": "No breach found. The Deputy Commissioner for Personal Data Protection determined that the complainants had provided valid consent in their Associate's Agreements with SLPS for disclosure to related corporations to facilitate real estate brokerage services, which encompassed the data sharing necessitated by the merger. The disclosure to CEA was also compliant as it was required under the Estate Agents Act 2010, which takes precedence under PDPA section 4(6).",
